      <HorSection2
        title="What are Limits?"
        id="Limits_Definition"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        A limit is a value that a function approaches as the input approaches a certain number. <br>The general form is: <br><br>
        y = a•bx where: <br><br>
        •a is a constant (initial value). <br> 
        •b is the base, and it’s typically a positive real number. <br>
        •x is the exponent. <br> 
        Exponential Function: f(x) = a • t <br>
      </HorSection2>

        <HorSection2
        title="Direct Substitution with Limits"
        id="Title_DS"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
       Direct substitution is a method for evaluating limits by directly replacing the variable with the value it is approaching. <br>
        If the function is continuous at that point, the limit equals the value of the function at that input. <br>
      </HorSection2>

       <HorSection2
        title="Direct Substitution with Exponential Functions"
        id="DS_Expo"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
        Direct substitution with exponential functions is a method for evaluating limits by plugging the value that x approaches directly into the function. <br><br>
        If the base of the exponential function is positive and the function is continuous at that point, the limit can be found simply by substitution. <br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)a"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        1. Solve for x in the equation: 2x = 8 <br>
        Solution: We need to express both sides of the equation with the same base. <br>
        Since 8 = 2³, we can rewrite the equation as: <br>
        2x = 2³ <br>
        Now that both sides have the same base, we set the exponents equal to each other: <br>
        x = 3 <br>
        Result: The value of x is 3. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)a"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        2. Solve for x in the equation: 5 • 3x = 45 <br>
        Solution: <br>
        Start by dividing both sides by 5: <br>
        5•3x / 5 = 45 / 5 <br>
        3x = 9 <br>
        Next, express 9 as a power of 3: <br>
        9 = 3² <br>
        Now the equation becomes: <br>
        3x = 3² <br>
        Since the bases are the same, set the exponents equal to each other: <br>
        x = 2 <br>
        Result: The value of x is 2. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="The Fractional Exponent: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 3: (Click to View)a"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        3. The Fractional Exponent Limit (Radical Form) <br>
        Problem: lim 9^(x/2), x → 4 <br>
        Solution: 9^(4/2) = 9² <br>
        9 × 9 = 81 <br>
        Since the function is continuous at x = 4, we plug it in: <br>
        Result: The limit is 81. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="The Power Function Limit: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 4: (Click to View)a"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        4. The Power Function Limit <br>
        In this case, we have a variable in both the base and the exponent. As long as the base is positive at the limit point, direct substitution remains our best friend. <br>
        Problem: lim (x - 1)^(x + 1), x → 3 <br>
        Solution: We substitute x = 3 into both the base and the exponent simultaneously: <br>
        Base: (3 - 1) = 2 <br>
        Exponent: (3 + 1) = 4 <br>
        Now, evaluate the resulting exponential expression: <br>
        2⁴ = 2 × 2 × 2 × 2 = 16 <br>
        Result: The limit is 16.
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

       <HorSection2
        title="Direct Substitution with Trigonometric Functions"
        id="DS_Trigo"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

        Definition: Trigonometric functions are functions of an angle. The basic trigonometric functions are: <br><br>
        Sine: sin (θ)<br>
        Cosine: cos (θ)<br>
        Tangent: tan (θ)<br>
        Secant: sec (θ)<br>
        Cosecant: csc (θ)<br>
        Cotangent: cot (θ)<br><br>

        Direct substitution with trigonometric functions is a method for evaluating limits by directly replacing x with the value it approaches. <br><br>
        If the trigonometric function is continuous at that point, the limit equals the value of the function at x. <br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="The Basic Sine Limit: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)b"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        1. The Basic Sine Limit <br>
        This example involves a simple trigonometric function. We can apply direct substitution here. <br>
        Problem: lim sin(x), as x → 30° <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = 30° directly into the sine function: <br>
        sin(30°) = 1/2 <br>
        Result: The limit is 1/2. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="The Basic Tangent Limit: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)b"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
         2. The Basic Tangent Limit <br>
        This example uses a simple trigonometric function. We can directly substitute here as well. <br>
        Problem: lim tan(x) as x → 45° <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = 45° directly into the tangent function: <br>
        tan(45°) = 1 <br>
        Result: The limit is 1. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="The Composite Root-Trig Limit: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 3: (Click to View)b"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        3. The Composite "Root-Trig" Limit <br>
        This example nests a trigonometric function inside a square root. For direct substitution to work, the value inside the square root must be non-negative. <br>
        Problem: lim √(2cos(x)), x → π/3 <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = π/3 directly into the cosine function: <br>
        cos(π/3) = 1/2 <br>
        Multiply by the constant: 2 • 1/2 = 1 <br>
        Apply the root: √1 = 1 <br>
        Result: The limit is 1. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example The Reciprocal Product Limit: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 4: (Click to View)b"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       4. The Reciprocal Product Limit <br>
        This example uses sec(x) (which is 1/cos(x)) and a squared term. Track multiple operations at once. <br>
        Problem: lim sec²(x) • sin(x), x → π/6 <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = π/6 into both parts: <br>
        Find sec(π/6): cos(π/6) = √3/2 → sec(π/6) = 2/√3 <br>
        Square it: (2/√3)² = 4/3 <br>
        Find sin(π/6): sin(π/6) = 1/2 <br>
        Multiply them: 4/3 • 1/2 = 4/6 = 2/3 <br>
        Result: The limit is 2/3. <br>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Direct Substitution with Logarithmic Functions"
        id="DS_Log"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

       Definition: A logarithmic equation is the inverse of an exponential equation. The general form is: y = log<sub>b</sub>(x) <br>
        • b is the base. <br>
        • x is the argument. <br>
        • y is the result. <br><br>

      Logarithmic Function: f(x) = log<sub>b</sub>(x) <br>
        Properties: <br>
        • log<sub>b</sub>(b<sup>x</sup>) = x <br>
        • b<sup>log<sub>b</sub>(x)</sup> = x <br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)c"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       1. Problem: lim log<sub>2</sub>(x) = 5 <br>
        Solution: Rewrite the given equation in exponential form: <br>
        log<sub>2</sub>(x) = 5 → 2<sup>5</sup> = x <br>
        Result: x = 32 <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)c"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
         2. Problem: lim log<sub>3</sub>(x) = 4 <br>
        Solution: Rewrite the given equation in exponential form: <br>
        log<sub>3</sub>(x) = 4 → 3<sup>4</sup> = x <br>
        Result: x = 81 <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 3: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 3: (Click to View)c"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        3. Problem: lim log<sub>2</sub>(2x - 5), as x → 3 <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = 3 into the expression and simplify: <br>
        log<sub>2</sub>[2(3) - 5] <br>
        = log<sub>2</sub>(6 - 5) <br>
        = log<sub>2</sub>(1) <br>
        Since 2<sup>0</sup> = 1, log<sub>2</sub>(1) = 0 <br>
        Result: The limit is 0 <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 4: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 4: (Click to View)c"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        4. Problem: lim log<sub>10</sub>((2x)/(x - 4)), as x → 5 <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = 5 into the fraction: <br>
        Numerator: 2(5) = 10 <br>
        Denominator: 5 - 4 = 1 <br>
        Fraction: 10/1 = 10 <br>
        Apply the logarithm: log<sub>10</sub>(10) <br>
        Since 10<sup>1</sup> = 10, log<sub>10</sub>(10) = 1 <br>
        Result: The limit is 1 <br>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

       <HorSection2
        title="Direct Substitution with Table of Values"
        id="Title_Table"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >
      Limits Using Table of Values is a method for estimating the limit of a function by observing the function’s output as the input values get closer to a certain number. <br><br>
        Steps: <br>
        • Choose x-values approaching the point of interest from both the left and the right. <br>
        • Calculate the corresponding f(x) values for each x. <br>
        • Observe the trend of f(x) as x gets closer to the target value. <br>
        • The value that f(x) approaches is the estimated limit. <br>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)d"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       Problem no. 1: f(x) = (3x - 1)/x, x → 1 <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = 1 directly into the expression: <br>
        (3(1) - 1)/1 = 2 <br>
        Make a table for x approaching 1 from the left and right: <br><br>

        Left-hand approach (x → 1⁻): <br>
        <table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
            <tr>
                <th>x</th>
                <th>f(x)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr><td>0.5</td><td>1.464</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.8</td><td>1.746</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.9</td><td>1.848</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.99</td><td>1.977</td></tr>
            <tr><td>0.999</td><td>1.997</td></tr>
        </table> <br>

        Right-hand approach (x → 1⁺): <br>
        <table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
            <tr>
                <th>x</th>
                <th>f(x)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr><td>1.001</td><td>2.004</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.01</td><td>2.02</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.1</td><td>2.05</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.2</td><td>2.045</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1.5</td><td>2.131</td></tr>
        </table> <br>

        Result: The limit of f(x) as x → 1 is 2 because both sides approach 2. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)d"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
         Problem no. 2: f(x) = (4x - 3)/x, x → 4 <br>
        Solution: Substitute x = 4 directly into the expression: <br>
        (4(4) - 3)/4 = 1 <br>
        Make a table for x approaching 4 from the left and right: <br><br>

        Left-hand approach (x → 4⁻): <br>
        <table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
            <tr>
                <th>x</th>
                <th>f(x)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr><td>3</td><td>1</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.5</td><td>2</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.9</td><td>3.48220</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.99</td><td>3.94493</td></tr>
            <tr><td>3.999</td><td>3.99446</td></tr>
        </table> <br>

        Right-hand approach (x → 4⁺): <br>
        <table border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
            <tr>
                <th>x</th>
                <th>f(x)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr><td>4.001</td><td>4.00555</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.01</td><td>4.05584</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.1</td><td>4.59479</td></tr>
            <tr><td>4.5</td><td>8</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5</td><td>16</td></tr>
        </table> <br>

        Result: From both the left and right, f(x) approaches 4. Therefore, the overall limit of f(x) as x → 4 is 4. <br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 3: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 3: (Click to View)d"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       <h3>Problem 3: lim<sub>x → 0</sub> (x / sin x)</h3>
        <p>Solution: Using a table of values to estimate the limit from both sides.</p>

        <p>Left-hand approach (x → 0⁻):</p>
