      </HorSection2>
      
      <HorSection2
        title="Limits of IF 0/0 (Indeterminate Form)"
        id="Title_IF"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

      0/0 is an indeterminate form because it does not have a unique solution. It can arise in limits, and further analysis (like L'Hopital’s Rule) is needed. <br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)e"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        1. Problem: Evaluate the limit: <br>
       Solution: <br>
       Using L'Hopital's Rule: <br>
       Since the direct substitution gives 0/0, we apply L'Hopital's Rule, which involves differentiating the numerator and denominator: <br><br>
       d/dx[sin(x)] = cos(x) <br>
       d/dx[x] = 1 <br><br>
       Now, substitute the derivatives into the limit: <br>
       lim<sub>x→0</sub> cos(x)/1 <br>
       Substitute x = 0: <br>
       cos(0) = 1 <br>
       Result: The limit is 1. <br><br>
         </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)e"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       2. Problem: Evaluate the limit: <br>
       lim<sub>x→1</sub> (x² - 1)/(x - 1) <br>
       Solution: <br>
       Direct substitution gives 0/0, so we apply factoring to simplify the expression. <br>
       Factor the numerator: <br>
       x² - 1 = (x - 1)(x + 1) <br>
       Now, the expression becomes: <br>
       (x - 1)(x + 1)/(x - 1) <br>
       Cancel out the common factor of (x - 1): <br>
       x + 1 <br>
       Substitute x = 1: <br>
       1 + 1 <br>
       Result: The limit is 2. <br><br>
         </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 3: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 3: (Click to View)e"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        3. The Algebraic Factoring Method <br>
       Problem: Find the limit of (x² - 9)/(x - 3) as x → 3 <br>
       Solution: simplify the given expression <br>
       (x - 3)(x + 3)/(x - 3) <br>
       The (x - 3) terms cancel out, leaving us with lim (x + 3) as x → 3 <br>
       Solve: x + 3 = 3 + 3 = 6 <br>
       Result: The limit is 6. <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 4: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 4: (Click to View)e"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        4. Problem: Find the limit of the following function as x approaches 3: <br>
       lim<sub>x→3</sub> (x² - 2x - 3)/(x - 3) <br>
       Solution: Find the factors of the numerator <br>
       We need two numbers that multiply to -3 and add to -2. Those numbers are -3 and 1. <br>
       x² - 2x - 3 = (x - 3)(x + 1) <br>
       Now the expression becomes: <br>
       (x - 3)(x + 1)/(x - 3) <br>
       Simplify: <br>
       As long as x ≠ 3 (which is true for the "approach" of a limit), we can cancel out the common (x - 3) term: <br>
       (x - 3)(x + 1)/(x - 3) = x + 1 <br>
       Re-evaluate the limit: <br>
       x + 1 = 3 + 1 = 4 <br>
       Result: The limit is 4. <br>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="One-Sided Limits (OSL)"
        id="Title_OSL"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

      A one-sided limit is the value that a function approaches from one direction (either from the left or the right). <br>
      Left-hand limit: lim as x→a- <br>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)f"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
         1. Evaluate the one-sided limit: <br>
       lim<sub>x→0+</sub> 1/x <br>
       Solution: As x→0+, 1/x approaches infinity: <br>
       lim<sub>x→0+</sub> 1/x = +∞ <br><br>
       </Accordion>
        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)f"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       2. Evaluate the one-sided limit: <br>
       lim<sub>x→0-</sub> 1/x <br>
       Solution: As x→0-, 1/x approaches negative infinity: <br>
       lim<sub>x→0-</sub> 1/x = -∞ <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 3: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 3: (Click to View)f"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        3. Problem: Given the function below, find lim f(x) as x→1-  and lim f(x) as x→1+ <br>
       f(x) = x + 2  if x &lt; 1  <br>
        f(x) = x² - 4  if x &ge; 1  <br>
       Solution: Find the value approaching from the left and right of 1 <br>
       Approach from the left (x→1-): <br>
       When x is less than 1, we use the top piece of the function: f(x) = x + 2 <br>
       Plug x = 1 into that equation: <br>
       1 + 2 = 3 <br><br>
       Approach from the right (x→1+): <br>
       When x is greater than or equal to 1, we use the bottom piece: f(x) = x² - 4 <br>
       Plug x = 1 into that equation: <br>
       (1)² - 4 = 1 - 4 = -3 <br><br>
       Result: Left-hand limit (x→1-) = 3 <br>
               Right-hand limit (x→1+) = -3 <br>
               Overall limit: DNE <br><br>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 4: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 4: (Click to View)f"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       4. Problem: Find the one-sided limits and overall limit of f(x) as x approaches 2 <br>
       f(x) = 3x - 4  if x &lt; 2 <br>
              x² - 2    if x &ge; 2 <br>
       Solution: Find the value approaching 2 from the left and right <br><br>

       Evaluate the Left-Hand Limit (x → 2⁻): <br>
       When x approaches from the left, x &lt; 2, so we use the top piece: f(x) = 3x - 4 <br>
       Plug in x = 2: <br>
       3(2) - 4 = 6 - 4 = 2 <br><br>

       Evaluate the Right-Hand Limit (x → 2⁺): <br>
       When x approaches from the right, x &ge; 2, so we use the bottom piece: f(x) = x² - 2 <br>
       Plug in x = 2: <br>
       (2)² - 2 = 4 - 2 = 2 <br><br>

       Result: Left-Hand Limit = 2 <br>
               Right-Hand Limit = 2 <br>
               Overall Limit = 2 <br>
        </Accordion>

      </HorSection2>

      <HorSection2
        title="Infinite Limits"
        id="Title_Infinite"
        direction="left"
        fontsize1="4rem"
        fontsize2="2rem"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        width="100%"
      >

      Definition: An infinite limit occurs when the value of a function increases or decreases without bound as the input approaches a certain number.<br><br>
      If f(x) → ∞ as x → a, the function grows positively without bound.<br>
      If f(x) → -∞ as x → a, the function decreases negatively without bound.<br><br>
      Infinite limits often indicate a vertical asymptote at x = a.<br><br>

        <Accordion
        title="Example 1: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 1: (Click to View)g"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
        1. Problem: Find the limit of f(x) = 1/x² as x → 0 <br>
        Solution: <br>
        Look at the right-hand side (x → 0⁺) <br>
        Pick a tiny positive number like 0.1 <br>
        0.1² = 0.01 <br>
        1 / 0.01 = 100 <br>
        As x gets even smaller (like 0.001), the result becomes 1,000,000. It is heading towards +∞. <br>
        Look at the left-hand side (x → 0⁻) <br>
        Pick a tiny negative number like -0.01 <br>
        When you square a negative, it becomes positive: (-0.01)² = 0.0001 <br>
        1 / 0.0001 = 10,000 <br>
        Even though x started negative, x² is positive. So this also heads toward +∞ <br>
        Result: Left side (x → 0⁻) = +∞ <br>
                Right side (x → 0⁺) = +∞ <br>
                Overall limit: Since both sides go to +∞, the overall limit is ∞ <br><br>
       </Accordion>
        <Accordion
        title="Example 2: (Click to View)"
        id="Example 2: (Click to View)g"
        direction="left"
        justifycontent="flex-start"
        fontsize1="2rem"
        fontsize2="1.5rem"
        >
       2. Problem: Find the limit of f(x) = 2x / (x - 1) as x → 1 <br>
        Solution: <br>
        Find the right-hand limit (x → 1⁺) <br>
        Imagine a number slightly bigger than 1, like 1.01 <br>
        Numerator: 2(1.01) ≈ 2 (positive number) <br>
        Denominator: 1.01 - 1 = 0.01 (a tiny positive number) <br>
        lim 2x / (x - 1) → +∞ <br>
        Find the left-hand limit (x → 1⁻) <br>
        Imagine a number slightly smaller than 1, like 0.99 <br>
        Numerator: 2(0.99) ≈ 2 (positive number) <br>
        Denominator: 0.99 - 1 = -0.01 (a negative number) <br>
        lim 2x / (x - 1) → -∞ <br>
        Result: Right-Hand Limit (x → 1⁺) = +∞ <br>
                Left-Hand Limit (x → 1⁻) = -∞ <br>
                Overall Limit: The two sides are heading in opposite directions, therefore the limit is DNE <br>
        </Accordion>
      </HorSection2>

